	                <h1>
    	                <span id="Template_NewsDate1_lblDate" style="float:right">16 December 2011 14:46</span>

	                    Bogus caller warning


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p>Lothian and Borders Police are issuing a warning to communities
and appealing for witnesses, following bogus caller incidents in
West Lothian.<br />
<br />
The first incident was reported to police on 15 December, when two
suspects visited a house in Clement Rise in Livingston, between
noon on 14 December and noon on 15th December.<br />
<br />
They spoke to the 62 year old homeowner and convinced her that roof
tiles&nbsp;required repairing.<br />
<br />
After initially agreeing a price, the suspects then forced the
complainer to hand over much more money, before failing to carry
out the work.<br />
<br />
The two suspects are described as male, and one of the men is
described as being of average height, thin build, and wearing a
blue cap. There is no further description of the second
suspect.<br />
<br />
They left in a Ford Transit panel van.<br />
<br />
A similar incident was reported in Ambrose Rise, where police were
called to the home of an 82-year-old disabled woman who had been
approached earlier on in the afternoon of the 15 December.<br />
<br />
Two males convinced the victim to part with a three-figure sum of
money before leaving and failing to carry out any work.<br />
<br />
The third incident happened at Caroline Park, Mid Calder between
12.30pm and 4pm on 15 December, when a 65-year-old female was
approached by two men offering to replace roof tiles for a small
sum of money.<br />
<br />
As with the first incident, the men quickly upped the price after
stating they had found other problems with the roof before quoting
a four figure fee to fix all the damage.<br />
<br />
The victim then said she had to ask her friend for further
guidance, after which the suspects left without getting any
money.<br />
<br />
The first suspect in this incident is described as being white,
around 60 years old, around 5ft 9inches tall, and of stocky
build.<br />
<br />
He had short dark hair and was clean shaven, and was wearing a navy
blue shell-suit top with no markings. He is described as having
unclear speech.<br />
<br />
The second suspect is described as white, around 20 years old, and
around 5ft 10inches tall. He is described as being of medium build,
and also had dark short hair.<br />
<br />
Anyone who remembers seeing the suspects at any of these locations
and can assist in identifying them is asked to come forward.<br />
<br />
A police spokesman said: "in each of these cases, the suspects have
approached victims with a plausible story and quotation before
quickly upping their prices and pressurising their targets to part
with more money.<br />
<br />
"It is essential that our communities are entirely sure of a
caller's identity before allowing them access to your
property.<br />
<br />
"Anyone who believes they are being pressured by a caller into
undertaking work should be sure of their identify first and always
ask for formal identification and a full, written quotation.<br />
<br />
"Our communities are also urged to be vigilant for any suspicious
people calling at the door of elderly neighbours and report any
concerns to their local policing teams."<br />
<br />
Anyone with any information can contact Lothian and Borders Police
on 0131 311 3131, or the charity Crimestoppers in confidence and
complete anonymity on 0800 555 111.</p>
